"""
context layer: Joshua 24.
Ch 24 (33 v): Shechem covenant renewal — historical recital, covenant challenge,
three-fold response, stone witness, Joseph's bones, deaths of Joshua and Eleazar.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "24": {
    "1": "<p>Joshua assembled all the tribes at Shechem — the geographical center of Canaan and the patriarchal covenant site par excellence. Shechem is where Abraham built the first altar in Canaan at the oak of Moreh (Gen 12:6-7), where Jacob bought land and erected an altar (<em>El Elohe Yisra'el</em>, Gen 33:18-20), and where the Ebal covenant ceremony of chapter 8 was just performed. The choice of Shechem for the final covenant renewal is not accidental: the book of Joshua ends where it began in the patriarchal promise, at the land&rsquo;s covenantal center. The elders, heads, judges, and officers of Israel are summoned — the full covenant leadership — and they present themselves before God (<em>lifnei ha-Elohim</em>), suggesting the assembly is understood as a theophanic event, possibly at the sanctuary at Shechem.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The historical recital begins: &ldquo;This is what YHWH, the God of Israel, says&rdquo; (<em>koh amar YHWH Elohei Yisra'el</em>) — the standard prophetic messenger formula, indicating that Joshua speaks in the first person on behalf of YHWH through the recital. This form is characteristic of the Hittite suzerainty treaty structure, which begins with a preamble (identification of the suzerain) followed by a historical prologue recounting the suzerain&rsquo;s acts of beneficence toward the vassal. The phrase &ldquo;beyond the River&rdquo; (<em>me'ever hanahar</em>) refers to the Euphrates — the ancestral homeland of Terah and Abraham in Ur and Haran. The same phrase, <em>Ever haNahar</em>, is used in Ezra 4-6 for the Persian province &ldquo;Beyond the River,&rdquo; preserving the ancient Mesopotamian boundary terminology. The ancestral gods of Terah (<em>Elohim acherim</em>, &ldquo;other gods&rdquo;) indicate that YHWH&rsquo;s call of Abraham was a call out of polytheism, not merely a change of location — the covenant begins with a departure from ancestral religious practice.</p>",
    "3": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s first-person recounting of the Abraham story — &ldquo;I took your father Abraham from beyond the River, led him through all of Canaan, gave him many descendants, gave him Isaac&rdquo; — compresses Genesis 12-25 into a single sentence focused on divine initiative. The emphasis is on YHWH as the active agent throughout: &ldquo;I took... I led... I gave.&rdquo; The historical prologue&rsquo;s function in the suzerainty treaty form is to establish the moral basis of the vassal&rsquo;s loyalty: the great king has acted beneficently and repeatedly on the vassal&rsquo;s behalf, therefore the vassal owes exclusive loyalty. The theological point is identical: Israel&rsquo;s covenant obligation to YHWH rests not on Israel&rsquo;s achievement but on YHWH&rsquo;s prior, comprehensive, unilateral action.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The recital continues through Isaac, Jacob, and Esau — noting that Esau received the hill country of Seir (fulfilling the earlier Deuteronomic tradition of Esau&rsquo;s territorial grant, Deut 2:4-5, 22) while Jacob and his sons went down to Egypt. The contrast between Esau getting Seir and Jacob going to Egypt sets up the subsequent rescue as demonstrating YHWH&rsquo;s preferential act: Esau received his inheritance simply; Jacob/Israel required divine redemption from slavery. The descent to Egypt is presented as YHWH&rsquo;s act (though Genesis narrates it through Joseph&rsquo;s story) — the covenant history is told from the perspective of divine sovereign control over all events, including the Egyptian sojourn.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The sending of Moses and Aaron and the striking of Egypt recalls Exodus 1-15 in compressed form. The phrase &ldquo;what I did in its midst&rdquo; refers to the ten plagues and the Passover — YHWH&rsquo;s acts of judgment against Egypt and redemption of Israel performed through Moses and Aaron. The recital&rsquo;s function is not historical education (Israel knew this story) but covenantal confrontation: YHWH is naming his own acts as the foundation of his claim on Israel&rsquo;s loyalty. The pattern is the same as the Decalogue&rsquo;s preamble: &ldquo;I am YHWH your God who brought you out of Egypt, out of the house of slavery&rdquo; (Exod 20:2) — identity before obligation, act before command.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Reed Sea crossing — &ldquo;I brought your fathers out of Egypt, and you came to the sea, and the Egyptians pursued your fathers with chariots and horsemen to the Reed Sea (<em>Yam Suf</em>)&rdquo; — is the historical pivot of the recital. The narrative compression allows the exodus tradition to function as the paradigmatic act of divine rescue: Egypt as the great power, Israel as the escaped slaves, the sea as the impossible obstacle, and YHWH as the one who opens a way through. The recounting at Shechem connects the present covenant community to the generation that experienced the original exodus — the covenant is not merely inherited but inhabited by identifying with the ancestors&rsquo; experience.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The sea event is described from Israel&rsquo;s perspective: &ldquo;they cried out to YHWH, and he put darkness between you and the Egyptians and brought the sea upon them and covered them; and your eyes saw what I did in Egypt.&rdquo; The &ldquo;your eyes saw&rdquo; addresses the present assembly as if they were present at the exodus — the covenant solidarity formula that appears throughout Deuteronomy (&ldquo;you stood before YHWH at Horeb,&rdquo; Deut 4:10; &ldquo;YHWH made this covenant with us, with all of us who are alive here today,&rdquo; Deut 5:3). Covenant identity is trans-generational: all Israel is present at the paradigmatic acts of divine redemption, not merely the biological contemporaries. &ldquo;You lived in the wilderness for a long time&rdquo; — the forty years of wilderness wandering is acknowledged without elaboration; the recital skips over the rebellion narratives to focus on YHWH&rsquo;s sustained presence and provision.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Amorites east of the Jordan (the kingdoms of Sihon and Og, Num 21:21-35) are the first of the conquest victories recounted. YHWH&rsquo;s first-person agency continues: &ldquo;I gave them into your hand, and you possessed their land.&rdquo; The <em>cherem</em> of the Transjordanian kingdoms is not mentioned explicitly here — the emphasis is on the gift (<em>va'eten otam beyadechem</em>), not the destruction. This continues the historical prologue&rsquo;s rhetorical purpose: YHWH is presenting himself as the benefactor who freely gave victory, not the commander who imposed burdens.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The Balaam episode is introduced — &ldquo;Balak son of Zippor, king of Moab, arose and warred against Israel&rdquo; — which is not quite how Numbers 22 describes it (Balak did not go to war militarily but summoned Balaam to curse). The recital summarizes the episode as Balak&rsquo;s aggressive intent thwarted by YHWH. The summary function of the recital means it presents the theological significance rather than the narrative detail: Moab&rsquo;s attempt to use cursing as a weapon against Israel was foiled by YHWH who turned the curse into blessing. The Balaam episodes are among the most heavily attested texts outside the Bible — the Deir Alla inscription (eighth century BCE) mentions &ldquo;Balaam son of Beor, a seer of the gods,&rdquo; confirming Balaam&rsquo;s reputation as a professional diviner in the Transjordanian region.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;I would not listen to Balaam; he blessed you over and over, and I delivered you from his hand.&rdquo; The divine refusal to allow cursing is the point: YHWH&rsquo;s protection of Israel extended to the spiritual-ritual sphere, not just the military. ANE cursing was understood as an effective weapon — curses activated divine powers against enemies. YHWH&rsquo;s neutralization of Balaam&rsquo;s curses is thus a comprehensive protection: neither military force nor magical-ritual force can overcome Israel when YHWH is their suzerain. The phrase &ldquo;blessed you over and over&rdquo; (<em>varech barak</em>, intensive/repetitive) refers to the four Balaam oracles of Numbers 23-24, each of which turned out as a blessing over Balak&rsquo;s demand for cursing.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The Jordan crossing and the conquest of Jericho are combined in one verse — &ldquo;you crossed the Jordan and came to Jericho, and the leaders of Jericho fought against you.&rdquo; The list of peoples who &ldquo;fought against you&rdquo; (Amorites, Perizzites, Canaanites, Hittites, Girgashites, Hivites, Jebusites) is the standard seven-nation list of Canaanite inhabitants (cf. Deut 7:1) — a stereotyped list that represents the totality of opposition rather than a specific sequence of battles. The recital is not a military history but a theological summary; the seven nations serve as literary shorthand for &ldquo;all possible enemies,&rdquo; emphasizing that YHWH gave victory against the full range of opposition.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The <em>tzir'ah</em> (hornet/wasp) that YHWH sent before Israel to drive out the two kings of the Amorites is one of the most discussed verses in Joshua. Deuteronomy 7:20 also promises that YHWH will send the <em>tzir'ah</em> before Israel. Interpretations include: (1) literally — a swarm of insects that drove out Canaanites (some scholars cite Egyptian military campaigns using hornets/bees iconography); (2) metaphorically — panic and demoralization, as in Exod 23:28 (&ldquo;I will send terror ahead of you&rdquo;); (3) Egyptian military action — following John Garstang&rsquo;s proposal that <em>tzir'ah</em> relates to the Egyptian word for Egypt/pharaoh, suggesting that Egyptian campaigns softened Canaanite resistance before Israel arrived. The phrase &ldquo;not by your sword or by your bow&rdquo; is the key: whatever the mechanism, the theological claim is that Israel&rsquo;s victory was not by their military capability.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;I gave you a land on which you did not labor, cities which you did not build and you dwell in them, vineyards and olive groves which you did not plant and you eat from them.&rdquo; This verse is the climax of the historical prologue and the most comprehensive statement of the <em>gift</em> character of the land. Israel inhabits a ready-made civilization — cities, agriculture, infrastructure — that they did not create. The theological implications are significant: the land is pure gift, not reward for labor. This creates the covenant obligation of the verses that follow: how does a people respond to a benefactor who gave them everything? The Deuteronomic tradition returns to this image repeatedly (Deut 6:10-12: &ldquo;cities you did not build, houses full of all good things you did not fill&rdquo;) and uses it as both gift and warning — the ease of inhabiting others&rsquo; work creates the temptation to forget the giver.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;Now therefore fear YHWH and serve him in sincerity and faithfulness&rdquo; — the covenant stipulation follows the historical prologue (the same structure as the Decalogue: Exod 20:2 preamble, then 20:3-17 stipulations). &ldquo;Remove the gods your fathers served beyond the River and in Egypt&rdquo; — the command reveals that idolatry was a live issue, not merely hypothetical. Three categories of forbidden gods are named: (1) the Mesopotamian ancestral gods of Terah (v. 2); (2) the Egyptian gods worshiped during the slavery period; (3) the Canaanite Baalim (implied by the ongoing context). The Shechem assembly is thus a purification assembly as well as a covenant renewal — the community must actively dispose of foreign cult objects. The terms <em>tamim</em> (sincerity/wholeness) and <em>emet</em> (faithfulness/truth) for the quality of service are the same pair that describes divine character (<em>chesed ve'emet</em>, loyal love and truth) — Israel&rsquo;s service should reflect the character of the God they serve.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Joshua&rsquo;s famous declaration — &ldquo;But as for me and my house, we will serve YHWH&rdquo; — is preceded by the covenant challenge: &ldquo;Choose this day whom you will serve.&rdquo; The <em>hayom</em> (this day) is the covenant&rsquo;s urgency formula: the covenant is not an abstract future aspiration but a decision demanded in the present moment. The options presented are specific: the Mesopotamian ancestral gods, the Canaanite Amorite gods of the land they now inhabit — both real cult systems with active priesthoods and temples in the region. The formulation is remarkable in assuming freedom of choice in the covenant relationship: YHWH does not compel worship but invites decision. Joshua&rsquo;s personal commitment (&ldquo;as for me and my house&rdquo;) — the anaphoric <em>anochi</em> (&ldquo;as for me&rdquo;) distinguishing himself from the assembly&rsquo;s deliberation — is the leader&rsquo;s exemplary commitment that precedes the people&rsquo;s response.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The people&rsquo;s first response — &ldquo;Far be it from us (<em>chalilah lanu</em>) to forsake YHWH to serve other gods&rdquo; — uses the strongest Hebrew rejection formula, the same phrase used by the eastern tribes in Joshua 22:29 (<em>chalilah lanu</em> = &ldquo;far be it from us, God forbid&rdquo;). The response is immediate and emphatic, but Joshua will challenge it (vv. 19-20): enthusiastic initial commitment is not the same as considered covenant fidelity. The dynamic mirrors Sinai, where Israel declared &ldquo;all that YHWH has spoken we will do&rdquo; (Exod 19:8; 24:3) before the golden calf episode. Joshua&rsquo;s challenge to their response is not cynicism but pastoral wisdom about the nature of covenant commitment.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The people articulate the basis of their commitment — recounting the exodus, the wilderness signs, and the conquest: &ldquo;It is YHWH our God who brought us and our fathers up from the land of Egypt, from the house of slavery.&rdquo; This is the people&rsquo;s own rehearsal of the historical prologue Joshua just delivered — they have absorbed the recital and now repeat it as the basis of their own decision. This is the intended effect of the historical prologue: the vassal&rsquo;s response demonstrates that they have internalized the suzerain&rsquo;s acts of beneficence. The covenant is not imposed but acknowledged as the fitting response to the known facts of their history.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The people&rsquo;s summary — &ldquo;YHWH drove out before us all the peoples, even the Amorites who lived in the land; we also will serve YHWH, for he is our God&rdquo; — completes their first response. The phrase &ldquo;he is our God&rdquo; (<em>Elohenu hu</em>) is the covenant formula of mutual belonging, the positive form of the covenant declaration (&ldquo;I will be your God and you will be my people,&rdquo; Jer 7:23; Ezek 36:28). The people are claiming the covenant relationship, not merely accepting a legal obligation. Joshua&rsquo;s counter-challenge in verses 19-20 does not deny this but intensifies it: claiming the covenant relationship means knowing who YHWH is — a holy God who will not tolerate covenant betrayal.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Joshua&rsquo;s counter-challenge — &ldquo;You are not able to serve YHWH, for he is a holy God (<em>Elohim kedoshim hu</em>), a jealous God (<em>El kanna hu</em>)&rdquo; — is one of the most striking pastoral moves in the OT. The leader who just challenged them to choose YHWH is now warning them that their enthusiastic response may not survive contact with the reality of who YHWH is. The grammatically unusual <em>Elohim kedoshim</em> (&ldquo;holy God&rdquo; with a plural form of &ldquo;holy&rdquo; for a singular God) may reflect an intensification — the plural of majesty or an emphatic form emphasizing absolute holiness. <em>El kanna</em> (&ldquo;jealous God&rdquo;) is from the second commandment (Exod 20:5), where YHWH declares his jealousy against those who serve other gods. Joshua is invoking the Sinai covenant language to warn the assembly: you are entering a covenant with a God whose character requires total exclusive loyalty, and your failure will not be met with indifference but with covenant consequence.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;If you forsake YHWH and serve foreign gods, he will turn and do you harm and consume you, after having done you good.&rdquo; The covenant curse is stated with almost shocking directness: the same YHWH who gave them everything (v. 13) will turn to do them harm if they break covenant. The phrase &ldquo;after having done you good&rdquo; intensifies the warning — YHWH&rsquo;s gift-giving is not a guarantee of future blessing but a demonstration of who he is and what he requires in return. The Deuteronomic covenant theology of blessing and curse is in full operation: the same covenant relationship that generates the blessing of the land generates the curse of exile for covenant violation (Deut 28-30). Joshua is the pastoral wisdom teacher who will not let his congregation embrace covenant without understanding its full weight.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The people&rsquo;s second affirmation — &ldquo;No, we will serve YHWH&rdquo; — is brief and simple after the full rehearsal of vv. 16-18. Having been challenged by Joshua&rsquo;s warning, they reaffirm. The simplicity of the response after the warning is significant: they have been given opportunity to reconsider but maintain their commitment. The covenant is now being entered with eyes open to both the privilege (all of vv. 2-13) and the cost (vv. 19-20). This is a more mature covenant commitment than the initial enthusiastic response.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Joshua declares: &ldquo;You are witnesses against yourselves (<em>edim atem bachem</em>) that you have chosen YHWH to serve him.&rdquo; The self-witness formula — the people become witnesses to their own covenant decision — creates a legally binding self-declaration. In the ANE treaty context, witnesses are the guarantors of the covenant; here the covenant community itself functions as the witness. This is a sophisticated covenantal move: the people cannot later claim ignorance or coercion, because they have declared themselves witnesses to their own free choice. The formula appears also in 1 Samuel 12:5 (Samuel&rsquo;s farewell: &ldquo;you are witnesses, and YHWH is witness&rdquo;) as the standard structure for a covenant witnessed by the parties themselves and by God.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;Now therefore remove the foreign gods that are among you, and incline your hearts to YHWH, the God of Israel.&rdquo; The practical command follows the covenant commitment: the presence of foreign cult objects in the community is incompatible with the covenant just renewed. The phrase &ldquo;among you&rdquo; (<em>bekirbechem</em>) implies that such objects were actually present — not merely a hypothetical. Jacob&rsquo;s household buried their foreign gods at Shechem under the oak (Gen 35:2-4): &ldquo;They gave Jacob all the foreign gods they had and the rings in their ears, and Jacob buried them under the oak near Shechem.&rdquo; The Shechem covenant renewal is thus the typological fulfillment of Jacob&rsquo;s act: the entire nation does at Shechem what Jacob&rsquo;s household did at Shechem. The oak of Moreh (Gen 12:6; 35:4) and the oak at Shechem in Joshua 24:26 are likely the same or adjacent sacred tree — the covenant&rsquo;s continuity is written into the geography.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The people&rsquo;s third affirmation — &ldquo;YHWH our God we will serve, and his voice we will obey&rdquo; — completes the covenant exchange. The three-fold structure (vv. 16-18 first affirmation, v. 21 second affirmation, v. 24 third affirmation) reflects the intensity and durability of the covenant ratification. Each affirmation is made after increasing challenge: after Joshua&rsquo;s initial challenge (v. 15), after his warning about YHWH&rsquo;s holiness (vv. 19-20), and after the self-witness formula (v. 22). The three-fold structure in covenant contexts signals completeness and irrevocability — the people have committed publicly, after warning, under self-witness.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Joshua made a covenant (<em>karat brit</em>) with the people that day and set a statute and an ordinance for them at Shechem. The technical phrase <em>karat brit</em> (lit. &ldquo;cut a covenant&rdquo;) refers to the covenant-making ceremony involving a sacrificial act (cf. Gen 15:17, the covenant with Abraham; Exod 24:5-8, the Sinai covenant blood-ratification). The covenant at Shechem is thus the covenant renewal that closes the book of Joshua: Israel has entered the land, distributed it, held the Ebal ceremony (ch. 8), and now in the final chapter ratifies their covenant commitment at Shechem with the full covenant assembly. The &ldquo;statute and ordinance&rdquo; (<em>chok umishpat</em>) that Joshua sets suggests a formal legal document was produced — matching the covenant treaty&rsquo;s document clause requirement.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Joshua wrote these words in the Book of the Law of God (<em>Sefer Torat Elohim</em>) and set up a great stone under the oak that was in the sanctuary of YHWH. The <em>Sefer Torat Elohim</em> is either the Pentateuch or a specifically Joshuanic covenant document; either way, the written record is the fulfillment of the Deuteronomic document clause (Deut 31:24-26: Moses wrote the Torah and placed it beside the ark as a witness). The great stone (<em>even gedolah</em>) set under the oak is a <em>massebah</em> — standing stone witness — analogous to Jacob&rsquo;s pillar at Bethel (Gen 28:18), the Laban-Jacob heap of stones (Gen 31:45-52), and the Ebal altar-stones (ch. 8). The oak at Shechem under which Jacob buried the foreign gods (Gen 35:4) is now the site of the covenant witness stone — the tree that witnessed the purging of idols is now the tree that witnesses the covenant renewal. The entire patriarchal-Joshua covenant arc is consummated in this geography.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&ldquo;This stone shall be a witness against us (<em>edah ven tihyeh banu</em>), for it has heard all the words of YHWH that he spoke to us; it will be a witness against you if you deal falsely with your God.&rdquo; The personified stone-as-witness is a bold legal metaphor: the stone that &ldquo;heard&rdquo; the covenant declaration becomes its permanent witness. The combination of written document (v. 26) and material witness (v. 27) matches the ANE treaty format precisely — the Hittite treaties specified both the written text and the divine witnesses. Here the divine witnesses are replaced by the community as self-witnesses (v. 22) and the stone as environmental witness. The formula &ldquo;if you deal falsely with your God&rdquo; (<em>im tekahasun b'Eloheichem</em>) anticipates the Judges narrative: the generation after Joshua will do exactly this.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Joshua dismissed the people, each to his inheritance — the book&rsquo;s final act of distribution, matching the inheritance-allocation work of chapters 13-22. The return to individual tribal territories is the covenant&rsquo;s practical form: each family living on its allotted land, under covenant obligation, as the enacted form of the covenant relationship. The inheritance (<em>nachalah</em>) is simultaneously the land-gift and the covenant-bond; to live on the land is to live in covenanted relationship with YHWH.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Joshua the son of Nun, the servant of YHWH (<em>eved YHWH</em>), died at the age of one hundred and ten years. The title <em>eved YHWH</em> (servant of YHWH) is the same title given to Moses throughout Deuteronomy and Joshua (Deut 34:5; Josh 1:1, 13, 15). Joshua receiving the same honorific at death signals that he has fulfilled the same covenantal role as Moses: the servant who received YHWH&rsquo;s commission and executed it faithfully. The age at death — one hundred and ten years — is the same as Joseph (Gen 50:26). The identical death-age is a typological marker: Joshua and Joseph are the two figures in Israel&rsquo;s history who successfully brought Israel through major transitions (Joseph into Egypt, Joshua into Canaan), and their identical lifespans signal their structural equivalence in the covenant story.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Joshua was buried in the territory of his inheritance at Timnath-serah in the hill country of Ephraim, north of Mount Gaash. Timnath-serah was given to Joshua by Israel at his request (Josh 19:50) — the leader who distributed the land to all the tribes received his own portion last and was buried there. The burial at the inheritance is the covenant&rsquo;s final personal enactment: Joshua&rsquo;s body rests in the land YHWH gave him, a physical testimony to the covenant&rsquo;s fulfillment in his own life. The hill country of Ephraim connects Joshua&rsquo;s burial to the tribal territory of Joseph&rsquo;s son — appropriate for the Joshua-Joseph typological parallel.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&ldquo;Israel served YHWH all the days of Joshua, and all the days of the elders who outlived Joshua and had known all the work that YHWH had done for Israel.&rdquo; This is the book&rsquo;s most important closing theological verdict: faithfulness lasted through the generation that experienced YHWH&rsquo;s acts and through the generation that personally knew those who had. Judges 2:10 picks up exactly where this verse ends: &ldquo;And all that generation also were gathered to their fathers. And there arose another generation after them who did not know YHWH or the work that he had done for Israel.&rdquo; The faithfulness was one-generational beyond Joshua — it extended only as far as living memory of YHWH&rsquo;s acts reached. The implicit lesson: when the transmission of the covenant story fails, covenant faithfulness fails. The Shechem assembly&rsquo;s historical recital (vv. 2-13) is exactly the answer to this problem — the spoken, rehearsed, covenanted memory of what YHWH did is the mechanism for extending faithfulness beyond those who personally experienced it.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The bones of Joseph, which the Israelites had brought up from Egypt (Exod 13:19; Gen 50:25), were buried at Shechem in the portion of the field that Jacob had bought from the sons of Hamor (Gen 33:19-20) for a hundred pieces of silver. The burial of Joseph&rsquo;s bones at Shechem closes a narrative arc spanning four books of the Torah and Joshua: the dying Joseph commanded his bones to be carried back to Canaan (Gen 50:24-25), Moses carried them out of Egypt (Exod 13:19), Israel carried them through the wilderness, and Joshua brings them to rest at their patriarchal home. The specific site — Jacob&rsquo;s purchase from the sons of Hamor at Shechem — connects Joseph&rsquo;s burial to the patriarchal land-purchase, the first piece of Canaan ever in Israelite possession (before the conquest). Shechem/Sychar is later identified as the site of Jacob&rsquo;s well (John 4:5-6), connecting the patriarchal geography to the NT narrative at the same location. Joseph&rsquo;s bones becoming the inheritance of Joseph&rsquo;s descendants (the verse notes the land became the inheritance of the descendants of Joseph) makes the burial a covenantal act: the Joseph tribes inherit the land and the ancestor simultaneously.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Eleazar the son of Aaron died and was buried at Gibeah, the town of his son Phinehas, in the hill country of Ephraim. Eleazar&rsquo;s death closes the priestly line of the Exodus generation: Aaron died before the Jordan crossing (Num 20:28), and now Eleazar, who accompanied the land distribution and the Shechem assembly, dies. Eleazar&rsquo;s burial &ldquo;in the hill of Phinehas his son&rdquo; (<em>begiv'at Pinchas beno</em>) — the town given to Phinehas — creates the priestly succession link: the high priesthood passes to Phinehas (1 Chr 6:4), the zealous priest who turned away YHWH&rsquo;s anger at Baal Peor (Num 25:7-13) and who led the investigation of the eastern tribes&rsquo; altar (Josh 22:13-34). The book ends with three burials — Joshua (v. 30), Joseph&rsquo;s bones (v. 32), Eleazar (v. 33) — marking the completion of the transition generation. The military leader, the patriarch&rsquo;s bones, and the high priest are all at rest in the land, and the covenant has been enacted at Shechem. Israel is in the land; the covenant is ratified; the faithfulness of the generation that knew YHWH&rsquo;s works is the book&rsquo;s closing testimony and its implicit warning to every generation that follows.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'joshua')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'joshua', c)
    print('joshua ch 24: context written')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
